describe("done method behavior without callbacks", () => {
  it("should call Q.onerror with the rejection reason when done() is called with no callbacks on a rejected promise", (done) => {
    const originalOnerror = Q.onerror;
    const error = new Error("test rejection");

    Q.onerror = function (err: any) {
      Q.onerror = originalOnerror;
      expect(err).toBe(error);
      done();
    };

    // When done() is called with no callbacks, the original code uses `this` directly
    // (no extra .then() wrapper), while the mutated code always wraps with .then().
    // Both should eventually call Q.onerror, but the original skips the extra tick.
    // We test that Q.onerror is called exactly once (not zero times due to a broken chain).
    Q.reject(error).done();

    // Timeout to fail the test if onerror is never called
    setTimeout(() => {
      Q.onerror = originalOnerror;
      done(new Error("Q.onerror was never called"));
    }, 500);
  });
});
```

Wait, this test would pass on both versions. Let me focus on the specific case where `fulfilled` is falsy but provided - that won't differ. The real issue is when `fulfilled || rejected || progress` evaluates differently from `true`.

The test should check behavior when `done(null, null, null)` vs `done()` - with the mutation, `done(null, null, null)` would behave like `done()` in the original (since `null || null || null` is falsy).

```typescript
